Presenting GQ Men Of The Year 2022: Mo Amer (@moamer), photographed by Eric Johnson (@upstairsaterics) with words by Samira Larouci (@samiralarouci). 
 “Stand-up comedy saved my life. It gave me a source of therapy that, whether I knew I needed it or not, is really the best way to say how you feel about what’s going on inside you, or out there in the world.” - Mo Amer  Palestinian, but born in Kuwait and raised in Houston, Amer shot to fame as Mo, Ramy’s diner-owning cousin in the Golden Globe-winning series. Earlier this year, he released Mo, his eponymous series on Netflix – to much critical acclaim. Now splitting his time between New York, Los Angeles and Houston (“Always has been home, and always will be hopefully), his latest role in DC Comics Black Adam has catapulted him into the mainstream.
 
Read the full story on our website. 
 
Words: @samiralarouci
Photography: @upstairsaterics
Stylist: @tiffanistyles
Producer: @lem0nadia 
Makeup Artist: @yuisakamoto10
Photography Assistant: Malcolm Sales
Fashion Assistant: @audrasavannah

I remember when #Nas first hit the scene. He was/is sooooo official. Watching him on @videomusicbox in my youth. He was EVERYTHING🖤. Then to meet him & hang out & shoot him on multiple occasions. I think this was like 1995-96. We were all so young. Still one of my top 5’s👊🏽. In fact Nas & Kelis were 2 of the first artists to visit our Upstairs studio in midtown. This shit never gets old to me. What a wild eccentric life I’ve been living. Let’s keep it going. I’m still hungry❤️
And I wanna meet a bunch of you youngins at the Upstairs holiday thingy. Come say “What’s up” to uncle E❤️😘🙏🏽
Oh wow, somehow I don’t remember ever seeing this first image of me (left) from high school. I also don’t remember the homie on my right🤷🏾‍♂️
Happy Birthday @joeylabeija my love❤️😘🥂
Happy Birthday to this Beauty. @donchristianjones ❤️🥂😘

Happy Holidays from me & the girls🖤.

What a great way to wake up🙂. I’m obsessed with @glorillapimp. Didn’t know this was coming out so soon. Thanks to the entire team🙏🏽

REPOST via  @lrpeoples🖤
Last summer, you couldn’t go anywhere without hearing “F.N.F. (Let’s Go)” by 23-year-old Memphis native @glorillapimp. I proudly know the lyrics by heart and am so thrilled to see her having some of the best songs of the year and now being nominated for a Grammy, earning her rightful place among rap’s ratchet queens in a lineage that traces from Lil’ Kim to Nicki Minaj to Cardi B. Watching her, you can learn a thing or two about knowing your worth and asking for your due. I’m so excited for you all to see the rest of @thecut fashion issue and our celebration of 50 years of hip-hop throughout the year.

As seen in the pages of V142, V is celebrating the 50th anniversary of hip-hop in a new portfolio of the industry’s latest musical powerhouses as we connect two generations of female rapstresses that have forged their own path and have signaled the turn of a new era for the once male-dominated genre. 🎵

Meet @youngdevyn!

“My family’s from Trinidad, so we have a genre called Soca. And I got very big in the Soca genre because I started at eight years old. I blew up in the first six months, I was on tour from like eight years old to 14. I always felt like because I’m authentically from Trinidad and authentically from Brooklyn, I could kind of be the artist that bridges that gap and makes it mainstream. I never thought Hip Hop would ever be what it was, that kind of just happened organically.” Head to the link in bio to discover the full story + order your copy of V142 now at shop.vmagazine.com

I’m so proud to have taken this photo of #Ummah. The year was 1996 for Vibe magazine. I’m a huge fan of  J-Dilla as well as A Tribe called Quest. I love when my photos are the photos associated with a particular artist for life🙏🏽. I’ve been lucky to have been a part of so many important cultural moments👊🏽

The Ummah was a music production collective, composed of members Q-Tip and Ali Shaheed Muhammad of A Tribe Called Quest, and the late Jay Dee (also known as J Dilla) of the Detroit-based group Slum Village. Occasional members included Raphael Saadiq, and D'Angelo. In addition to producing nearly the entirety of A Tribe Called Quest's fourth and fifth albums, the Ummah provided backing tracks and remixes for a notable array of hip hop and contemporary R&B artists, including Busta Rhymes, Whitney Houston, Keith Murray, the Brand New Heavies, Michael Jackson, Janet Jackson, and Jon B. The group was so named because two of its members (Tip and Ali) are devout Muslims. The word "ummah" is Arabic for "community", "nation", or "brotherhood". Generally, the term refers to the global Muslim population.

#HEROES | ESG is one of those bands whose name is a passcode shared between those with excellent taste. The band’s biggest area of cultural prominence may be in hip-hop, where, since forming in the South Bronx in the late ‘70s, ESG’s primal beats have been a source of fascination to the point of obsession for DJs and rappers. “UFO,” ESG’s eerie, insistent, creepily beautiful instrumental, has been sampled hundreds of times by everyone from Big Daddy Kane and The Notorious B.I.G. to TLC and the Beastie Boys. 

Becoming a cult phenomenon is an honor, but it’s also super frustrating when you’ve created work that has profoundly shaped culture, yet only a handful of people know about it. That is, in part, why ESG co-founder and frontwoman Renee Scroggins has decided to tell ESG’s story on her own terms via a forthcoming documentary, ‘Are You Serious? The ESG Story’. “I’ve tried to work with other people,” Scroggins, who directed the film, says of past attempts to capture her band’s story on film. But it always wound up with someone “trying to, in so many words, screw me over,” she recalls, laughing over the phone. “I decided I can do it myself—just like everything else in ESG history.” Head to the link in our bio for the whole story + order your copy of V145 at shop.vmagazine.com. 
—
From V145 Winter 2023 Issue
